Step 1: Create VPC
Go to VPC Dashboard → Create VPC

Resources to create: VPC only

Name: my-vpc

IPv4 CIDR: 10.0.0.0/16

Click Create VPC

Step 2: Create Subnets
Go to Subnets → Create Subnet

Select VPC: my-vpc

Public Subnet:

Name: public-subnet

Availability Zone: us-east-1a

CIDR: 10.0.1.0/24

Private Subnet:

Name: private-subnet

Availability Zone: us-east-1a

CIDR: 10.0.2.0/24

Click Create Subnet

Step 3: Create and Attach Internet Gateway
Go to Internet Gateways → Create Internet Gateway

Name: my-igw

Click Create Internet Gateway

Select my-igw → Actions → Attach to VPC

Select my-vpc → Attach

Step 4: Create Route Table
Go to Route Tables → Create Route Table

Name: public-rt

Select VPC: my-vpc

Click Create

Add Route:

Select public-rt → Routes tab → Edit routes

Click Add route

Destination: 0.0.0.0/0

Target: Internet Gateway → Select my-igw

Click Save changes

Associate with Public Subnet:

Select public-rt → Subnet associations tab → Edit subnet associations

Select public-subnet

Click Save associations

PART 2: Launch Bastion Server (Public Subnet)
Step 5: Launch Bastion EC2 Instance
Via AWS Console:

Go to EC2 Dashboard → Launch Instance

Name: bastion-server

AMI: Ubuntu 22.04 (or 24.04)

Instance type: t2.micro

Key pair: Create or select existing → Name: bastion-key (download .pem file)

Network settings → Edit:

VPC: my-vpc

Subnet: public-subnet

Auto-assign public IP: Enable

Security group rules:

Type: SSH, Port: 22, Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Launch instance

After launch, note:

Public IP: 16.147.229.31 (from your example)

Private IP: 10.0.1.x

PART 3: Launch Database Server (Private Subnet)
Step 6: Launch Database EC2 Instance
Via AWS Console:

Launch Instance

Name: database-server

AMI: Amazon Linux 2 (or Ubuntu)

Instance type: t2.micro

Key pair: Create or select → Name: database-key (download .pem file)

Network settings → Edit:

VPC: my-vpc

Subnet: private-subnet

Auto-assign public IP: Disable

Security group rules:

Type: SSH, Port: 22, Source: 10.0.1.0/24 (Bastion subnet CIDR)

Launch instance

After launch, note:

Private IP: 10.0.2.16 (from your example)

No public IP

PART 4: SSH Commands
Step 7: SSH into Bastion Server (From Local Machine)
On your local terminal:

bash
# Set correct permission for bastion key
chmod 400 bastion.pem

# SSH into Bastion
ssh -i "bastion.pem" ubuntu@16.147.229.31
Expected output:

text
ubuntu@ip-10-0-1-xxx:~$
Step 8: Copy Database Key to Bastion Server
From your LOCAL machine (open new terminal):

bash
scp -i "bastion.pem" "database.pem" ubuntu@16.147.229.31:~/
Step 9: SSH from Bastion to Database Server
On Bastion server (already connected):

bash
# Set permission for database key
chmod 400 database.pem

# SSH to Database (using private IP)
ssh -i "database.pem" ec2-user@10.0.2.16
Accept host key: Type yes and press Enter

Expected output:

text
[ec2-user@ip-10-0-2-16 ~]$
